	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>Hello Judith and Madhatter</p>
<p>This is an interesting thread. &nbsp;I am a little older than you girls (in my late 60s) &nbsp;and I am eight months now on letrozole prior to surgery to shrink the tumour (4.8cms, now 2.5)for a lumpectomy. &nbsp;ONcologist appointment now not until end of March with another mammorgram in February, so by that time I will have be on this for nearly a year.</p>
<p>I empathise very much with you both about the side effects. &nbsp;I was having about 20 plus hot flashes per day in the beginning &nbsp;that begin with nausea and progress from there. &nbsp;These are now down to about eight per day, sometimes less. &nbsp;Joint pain is the real nightmare, but I am lucky, Madhatter, as I am able to walk every day for about 2-3 miles. &nbsp;I had a fall beginning of November and this left a small fracture ot my ankle and ligament injury. &nbsp;However Physio said it was okay to start walking again. &nbsp;It is difficult sometimes as my leg joints and muscles hurt a lot, but I am absolutely determined.</p>
<p>My memory is reasonably intact, but I have noticed a little difference looking for words now. &nbsp;Although retired, I have two very busy voluntary roles, one of which is on a support board as part of a moderation team and the other involves tutoring a course, so I have to be pretty decent cognitively.</p>
<p>When I finally have surgery, I am considering &nbsp;not doing the radiotherapy and I most certainly am not going to take AIs for 5 years if at all. &nbsp;A few weeks ago, my breast care nurse finally called me and when I told her that I was not sure about RT, she told me that I should do the RT, but if I did not want to continue on AIs then this would be the better option. &nbsp;I need to ask her more about this.&nbsp;</p>
<p>For me, and as I have written before, I want quality of life and if that will be less, so be it at my age.</p>
<p>Judith, I &nbsp;and so sorry for the things you have been through and I so understand your circumstances, although I am lucky as I have a son, who lives in London. &nbsp;However, I live alone and have an extremely limited social network here in Newcastle upon Tyne. &nbsp;My friends are in London and Yorkshire. &nbsp;The guy I used to see, we didn&#39;t live together, but he stayed here with me a great deal, walked off into the sunset in September. &nbsp;I also come from a very dysfunctinal family and frankly have had 12 years of terrible things occurring culminating in breast cancer.</p>
<p>I try all the time to keep processing things in a positive way and to remember the serenity prayer.</p>
<p>God Grant me the serenity to accept those things I cannot change, the courage to change the things I can - and the wisdom to know the difference.</p>
<p>It sometimes seems unbearably hard and I am so sorry for the SEs after your surgery and RT with lymphodema and cellulitis. &nbsp;</p>
<p>IMHO, we have to keep on, keeping on and to make the present a positive force in order to make those good memories.</p>
<p>You are in my thoughts and thank you for all the time you take to post and help other people. &nbsp;You have helped me too:)</p>
<p>Wishing you hope, peace and love.</p>
<p>Heather X</p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  

