	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>Hi Madhatter</p>
<p>Many thanks for your thoughts in relation to RT. &nbsp;I will certainly take this on board in my decision, which will have course be down the road by a few months as surgery is dependent upon how much the tumour has decreased in size. Oncologist/surgeon &nbsp;needs it to be under 2cm or less for the lumpectomy and then of course a third of women have to go back for further surgery if they do not get all the margins.</p>
<p>I do understand how you must feel regarding physical intimacy and the effects of the letrozole. &nbsp;I have found Replens is very helpful used a few times per week, the other one, Sylk, that you can get on prescription is hopeless IMO. &nbsp;My surgery only prescribe Sylk, not Replens, maybe it is a cost thing, but I just buy a month&#39;s supply every month.</p>
<p>These decisions are difficult ones for us all and it appears as though all of us are different in how we experience these drugs and whether there will be&nbsp;further problems if we do not continue with them.</p>
<p>IMHO, it seems that the treatments for cancer have many side effects and it is still a very inexact science, but the medical profession do the very best they can with the drugs tested and available. &nbsp;Of course I know that all drugs have side effects and for me not taking letrozole prior to surgery is not an option, for obvious reasons:) &nbsp;It is the aftermath that troubles me and my oncologist has told me that a third of all women who have more than sentinal lymph nodes removed plus RT &nbsp;will get some lymphodema .</p>
<p>Unfortunately too, I read the MacMIllan article &#39;Cured But at What Cost&#39; where according to the stats 25% of all those who go through cancer treatment will have long term side effects. &nbsp;Of course many of us can have long term side effects from other drugs too, particularly where we have to be on them for life - so it is a choice and, for me, I want to be fully informed before I can make my decisions. &nbsp;</p>
<p>This site has helped tremendously to inform me and for this I am grateful.</p>
<p>Good wishes</p>
<p>Heather</p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  

