								<img src="/cfs-filesystemfile/__key/communityserver-components-imagefileviewer/communityserver-components-selectableavatars-64e6583d-e9be-44d9-a227-06c829b8c238/avatar.png_2D00_32x32.png" border="0" alt="Lady Pepys" />
							</a>
											</span>
				</td>
				<td class="post-author-user-cell fiji-post-author-user-cell evolution2-post-author-user-cell">
				   <div class="user-name-post-date fiji-user-name-post-date evolution2-user-name-post-date">
						Posted by <span class="user-name">
															<a class="internal-link view-user-profile" href="/members/lady-pepys">
									<span></span>Lady Pepys
								</a>
													</span>
						<div class="post-date">
							<span class="label">
																	<a href="/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/t/87484">on</a>
															</span>
							<span class="value"><a href='/cancer_types/breast-cancer/f/38/p/87484/825421#825421' class="internal-link view-post">2 Nov 2015 6:16 PM</a></span>
						</div>
																	</div>
				</td>
			</tr>
		</table>
	</div>
	
	
	<div class="post-content user-defined-markup">
					<p>Dear ladies,</p>
<p></p>
<p>Thank you all for this thread, which I have been following with interest.&nbsp; I am 57 and was diagnosed with stage 2,grade 2 lobular cancer in April 2014..3 tumours&nbsp;and microinvasion of 1 lymph node&nbsp;(though some invasion&nbsp;of blood vessels too). &nbsp; I had mastectomy, chemotherapy and radiotherapy followed by more recent surgery tor remove the tissue expander, which was causing a lot of problems.&nbsp; I started Letrozole last December.&nbsp; At first I didn&#39;t notice any side effects but now, 11 months later, I feel wrecked!&nbsp; I started to get arthritis in my right hip, which has become much worse recently.&nbsp; Sometimes I can barely stand after a long walk - I refuse to give up my beloved walking but god am I paying the price.&nbsp;&nbsp;Some days are better than others but I take painkillers every day and have been referred to an orthopaedic surgeon.&nbsp; My muscles and joints ache and I have all sorts of other side effects.&nbsp; No sex drive but that&#39;s the least of my problems right now.&nbsp; I no longer have a partner..he left fairly soon after my diagnosis.&nbsp; </p>
<p>The point is, do I carry on with a drug I feel is seriously affecting my quality of life or do I just grit my teeth and put up with the side effects?&nbsp; Five years seems like a long stretch.&nbsp; The tumours I had were quite large and I understand this puts me at greater risk of a recurrence, as does the fact that there was some vascular invasion.&nbsp; </p>
<p>I&#39;m weaning myself off antidepressants now as I don&#39;t think I really need them any more.&nbsp; Around the time I had radiotherapy in March (and working at the same time), I felt a little weepy and unable to cope so my GP prescribed Sertraline.&nbsp;&nbsp; I am a little concerned by all the drugs I take..paracetamol, Naproxen, Adcal and ferrous sulphate (chemo knocked my iron levels for six).&nbsp; I moved home on 1 September from London to Hastings.&nbsp; I have a lovely new house which I would like to do up but progress is slow because of my joints.&nbsp; I also plan to return to work, after a break of 4 months.&nbsp; Life has really changed and I want to take it all in my stride.&nbsp; Or should I say limp!</p>
<p>This thread has given me much food for thought.&nbsp; So good to know I&#39;m not alone.</p>
<p>Pepys xx</p><div style="clear:both;"></div>
					</div>

	



	  

